    history:
      "Leica's optical origins reach back to 1849, when mathematician and instrument maker Carl Kellner founded an Optisches Institut in Wetzlar; the workshop was acquired in 1869 by Ernst Leitz I, whose name it carried as Optische Werke Ernst Leitz for the next century. The company built microscopes and binoculars before engineer Oskar Barnack, working at Leitz, developed a compact 35 mm camera prototype (the Ur-Leica) in 1913–1914 to test motion-picture film outside the cine camera. The production Leica I, introduced at the Leipzig Spring Fair in 1925, established 35 mm photography as a serious medium and defined a new class of small, fast cameras for photojournalism, street photography, and scientific documentation.\n\nLeica's optical design heritage is inseparable from a succession of landmark lens computers. Max Berek created the original Leitz Elmar (1925), a Tessar-derivative four-element design, followed by the Hektor (1930) and Summar (1933) faster standards and the original Summicron 50 mm f/2 (1953) — the latter a collaboration with the recently-hired Walter Mandler. Mandler joined Ernst Leitz GmbH in 1946 and was transferred to Ernst Leitz Canada (ELCAN) in Midland, Ontario in 1952; from there he led the design of the Summicron-M 50 mm f/2 (1969 and 1979 revisions), the Summicron-M 90 mm f/2 (1980), the Summilux-M 35 mm f/1.4 (1961, pre-ASPH), and the Noctilux-M 50 mm f/1.0 (1976). The earlier aspherical Noctilux 50 mm f/1.2 (1966), the first production photographic lens with hand-ground aspherical surfaces, was designed in Wetzlar by Helmut Marx and Paul Sindel rather than at ELCAN.\n\nThe M-mount, introduced with the Leica M3 in 1954, established the bayonet standard still used on every Leica rangefinder produced today. The compact 27.95 mm flange focal distance enables a class of wide-angle and standard lenses with minimal retrofocus complexity — an advantage that has shaped every Leica lens designed for rangefinder bodies since. The M system continued evolving through the M2, M4, M6, M7, MP, and M-A film bodies and the digital M8, M9, Monochrom, M10, and M11 generations.\n\nLeica relocated from its century-old Wetzlar campus to a smaller plant in Solms, 10 km south, in 1986–1988 as a cost-saving measure during the period of Japanese SLR dominance, then in 2014 returned to a purpose-built campus — Leitz-Park — on the outskirts of Wetzlar, consolidating R&D, lens production, and the Leitz-Park-hosted museum and Ernst Leitz Wetzlar archives in a single site. Peter Karbe, head of optical design at Leica Camera AG from the late 1990s, extended the design tradition with aspherical and apochromatic constructions optimized for digital sensors. His APO-Summicron-M 50 mm f/2 ASPH (2012) is widely considered one of the finest photographic lenses ever made, with essentially perfect aberration correction across the full field, and the APO-Summicron-M 35 mm f/2 ASPH (2015) extended the line with fluorophosphate glass and KZFS-type flints for three-wavelength chromatic correction. Karbe also designed the fixed-lens Leica Q series — the Q (2015), Q2 (2019), and Q3 (2023) — around a Summilux 28 mm f/1.7 ASPH, and the SL system (introduced with the SL Typ 601 in 2015) opened the L-mount alliance with Panasonic and Sigma.\n\nLeica produces lenses in deliberately small volumes at the Leitz-Park Wetzlar facility — and, for some lines, at Ernst Leitz Canada's successor in Midland, Ontario and at Leica Aparelhos Ópticos de Precisão in Vila Nova de Famalicão, Portugal — with assembly, cementing, and final adjustment performed largely by hand. This manufacturing philosophy results in lenses that command substantial premiums but are widely regarded as benchmarks for the craft.",
